UML:TaggedValue.value: ISO 19130 Sensor and data models for imagery and gridded data
The geometry attribute holds the CV_DomainObject that is a member of this CV_GeometryValuePair.

A subtype of a feature. From the abstract specification, a Coverage is a two or more dimensional metaphor for features found on or near a portion of the Earth's Surface. Some examples of a Coverage would be a satellite image of a portion of the earth, a census tract for the city of New York and a DEM for a USGS 1x1 degree map sheet (Topic 6, OGC Abstract Specification, 1998)
A coverage is a subtype of a feature that has pairs of distinguished properties consisting of a geometry property and a function that is defined over the coordinate set that is defined (delineated) by the geometry (Herring, J. OGC Change Proposal 95-039r2)
The attribute domainExtent shall contain the extent of the spatiotemporal domain of the coverage. The data type EX_Extent, is defined in ISO 19103. Extents may be specified in both space and time.

The operation evaluate shall accept a DirectPosition as input and return the record of attribute values for that direct position. The data type Record is defined in ISO 19103. If the direct position passed is not in the spatiotemporal domain, then an error message shall be generated

The operation "evaluateInverse" shall accept a Record of values as input and return a set of CV_DomainObjects. Normally, this will be the set of CV_DomainObjects in the Domain that are associated with values equal to those in the input Record. However, the operation may return other CV_DomainObjects derived from those in the Domain, as specified by the application schema.
CV_InterpolationMethod is a list of codes that identify interpolation methods that may be used for evaluating continuous coverages.

The geometry attribute holds the CV_DomainObject that is a member of this CV_GeometryValuePair.
The value attribute holds the record of attribute values associated with this CV_DomainObject.
A surface with an associated value. Used in the definition of discrete (step function) surface coverage functions.
CV_DiscreteCoverage is a subclass of CV_Coverage that returns a single record of values for any direct position within a single geometric object in its spatiotemporal domain.
The geometry represented by the various offset vectors is in the image plane of the grid. For example, for orthorectified grids, these vectors are in a spatial reference system.
Default is row major, other values will be from enumeration to be determined at a later date.
{The size of "values" equlas the product of the integers in "offsetNumbers"}
A segment is a 1-dimensional geometric object that has a beginning (start) and end point.
A code list that identifies methods for handling cases where the DirectPosition input to the evaluate operation falls on the end of one CV_ValueSegment and the start of the next.

A telleslation of spatial domain using Thiessen Polygons.
The C_Function associated to the network is an interpolation method defined from the PointValuePairs that are the center of the polygons. The most common interpolation methods are "nearest neighbor", and "lost area".

A polygon whose boundaries define the area consisting of points that are closer to the center point than any other point in the defining set. The boundaries are the perpendicular bisectors of the lines between the points in the dual TIN. Also referred to as Voronoi Diagrams.

Triangulated Irregular Network (TIN) - A tessellation model usually of the earth's surface comprised of a network of non-overlapping triangles, not necessary co-planar. The vertices of the triangles form a set of irregular spaced elevation posts The Delaunay Triangulation method is commonly used to produce TINs with triangles that are approximately equiangular in shape.
Throws an exception if the point is not on the surface of the TIN.

Three non-colinear points and associated values used in interpolation of a coverage function. Usually associated with a TIN or a Triangulated Spline.
Constraint: The three associated points in the PointValuePairs are not co-linear
